Spare a thought for the family of Bramwel Chakunza, the 28-year-old man who died after reportedly being assaulted inside the cells at Kisii Central Police Station for violating the Covid-19 curfew.
As if the rest of year hadn’t been tough enough, they had to mourn at Christmas. Bramwel was only the latest victim of brutality by police officers purportedly enforcing Covid-19 containment rules.
 Kenya’s early response to the pandemic was actually defined by the more deaths attributed to incidents of police beating people for breaking curfew rules or not wearing masks than the virus itself! In Mombasa, hordes of thuggish men in uniform pounced on their victims with bludgeons. In Nandi, a police officer in June shot a man dead for not wearing a face mask.
Deep State might be real
Mike Sonko, the former Nairobi governor, got a rude gift for Christmas after he was booted out of office on December 18. His impeachment capped a rough 12 months during which he was dramatically arrested following a highway chase, charged with corruption, barred from stepping foot in his physical office at City Hall and made to surrender some of his powers to a military man.
Mr Sonko has consistently blamed his troubles on the ‘Deep State’ – a powerful cartel of unelected officials and businesspeople whose existence has divided opinion. But the methodical manner Mr Sonko’s downfall was orchestrated will reinforce the notion that the ‘Deep State’ is real.



